==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*budō-'', from Indo-European ''*bheudh-''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[biada]], Old Saxon [[biodan]] (Dutch [[bieden]]), Old High German [[biotan]] (German [[bieten]]), Old Norse [[bjóða]] (Swedish [[bjuda]] ‘command, show’), Gothic *𐌱𐌹𐌿𐌳𐌰𐌽 (attested in compounds).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πευθεσθαι]] ‘ask for’, Sanskrit [[बोधयित]] ‘wake’, Old Church Slavonic [[бъдети]] (Russian [[будить]] ‘wake’), Lithuanian [[budeti]] ‘awake’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'be:odan/}}

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''bēodan'''}} (class II strong)
# to [[offer]] or [[give]]
#:''Hafa arna þanc ðara, ðe ðu unc bude'': thanks for the kindnesses, which you offered us as host.
# to [[proclaim]], [[announce]]
#:''Geacas gear budon'': cuckoos announced the year.

